  <section xml:id="sec-subgroups">
    <title>Subgroups</title>

    <introduction>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <q>I have this fear of falling in front of large groups of people. That's why I tend not to wear heels.</q>
        </p>
        <attribution>Taylor Swift</attribution>
      </blockquote>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-subgrp-defn-ex">
      <title>Subgroup Basics</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-subgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A nonempty subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is called a <em>subgroup</em>, denoted <m>H\leq G</m>, <notation><usage><m>\leq</m></usage><description>subgroup</description></notation> provided <m>H</m> is a group under the multiplication law of <m>G</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            A subgroup <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is a <em>proper</em> subgroup, denoted <m>H&lt;G</m> if <m>H\neq G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-subgrouptest">
        <title>Subgroup Tests</title>
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If a subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is nonempty and closed under multiplication and inversion, then <m>H</m> is a subgroup.
                </p>
              </li>
    
              <li>
                <p>
                  If a subset <m>H</m> of a group <m>G</m> is nonempty and satisfies for all <m>x,y \in H</m>, <m>xy^{-1} \in H</m>, then <m>H</m> is a subgroup.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <proof>
          <p>
            We prove the one-step test first.
          </p>

          <p>
            Assume <m>H</m> is non-empty and for all <m>x,y \in H</m>, <m>xy^{-1} \in H</m>. Since <m>H</m> is non-empty, there is an <m>h \in H</m> and hence <m>e_G = hh^{-1} \in H</m>. Since <m>e_Gx=x=xe_G</m> for any <m>x\in H</m>, <m>e_G</m> is an identity element for <m>H</m>. For any <m>h \in H</m>, <m>h^{-1} = eh^{-1}  \in H</m>, and so every element of <m>H</m> has an inverse inside <m>H</m>. For <m>x,y  \in H</m> we have <m>y^{-1} \in H</m> and thus <m>xy = x(y^{-1})^{-1} \in H</m> and hence <m>H</m> is closed under <m>\cdot</m>. This means that the restriction of the group operation of <m>G</m> to <m>H</m> is a well-defined group operation. This operation is associative by the axioms for the group <m>G</m>. The axioms of a group have now been established for <m>(H, \cdot)</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Now we prove the two step test.
          </p>

          <p>
					Assume <m>H</m> is non-empty and closed under multiplication and inversion. Then, for <m>x,y\in H</m> we have <m>y^{-1}\in H</m> and <m>xy^{-1}\in H</m>. Since the hypothesis of the one-step test is satisfied, <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
        </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <example>
        <title>Common Subgroups</title>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\{e_G\}</m> and <m>G</m> are the <term>trivial subgroups</term> of <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Z\leq\Q\leq\R\leq\C</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\Q^\times\leq\R^\times\leq\C^\times</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>n\in\N</m> and define <m>n\Z=\{x\in\Z|x=nk\;\text{for some}\;k\in\Z\}</m>. Then <m>n\Z\leq\Z</m> for all <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </example>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-subgroup-properties">
        <title>Properties of Subgroups</title>
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <title>Transitivity of Subgroups</title>
                <p>
                  If <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> and <m>K</m> is a subgroup of <m>H</m>, then <m>K</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <title>Intersections of Subgroups</title>
                <p>
                  If <m>H_\alpha</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> for all <m>\alpha</m> in an index set <m>J</m>, then <m>H=\bigcap_{\alpha\in J} H_\alpha</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <title>Unions of Subgroups</title>
                <p>
                  Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>H</m>, <m>H'</m> subgroups. Prove that <m>H\cup H'</m> is a subgroup if and only if <m>H\subseteq H'</m> or <m>H'\subseteq H</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-abelian-and-cyclic-subgroups">
        <title>Subgroups of Abelian and Cyclic Groups</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>H</m> be a subgroup of a group <m>G</m>. If <m>G</m> is abelian then so is <m>H</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-groups-contained-in-groups-are-subgroups">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>H</m> and <m>G</m> be groups. If <m>H\sse G</m>, then <m>H\leq G</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </lemma>

      <definition xml:id="def-alternating-group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>alternating group</em> <m>A_n</m> is the subset of all even cycles of <m>S_n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-alternating-group-is-subgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>A_n</m> is a subgroup of <m>S_n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <definition xml:id="def-special-linear-group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>special linear group</em> with complex entries is defined
            <me>
              \SL_n(\C)=\{A \mid A = n\times n \;\text{matrix with entries in}\; \C, \det(A)=1\}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-slg-subgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>SL_n(\C)</m> is a subgroup of <m>GL_n(\C)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-center">
      <title>The Center of a Group</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-group-pcenter">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <em>center</em> of a group <m>G</m>, often written <m>Z(G)</m>, is the set of elements of <m>G</m> that commute with every element of <m>G</m>. That is, 
            <me>
              Z(G)=\{x \in G \, | \, xy = yx\,\text{ for all $y \in G$}\}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-center-is-subgroup">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>Z(G)</m> is an abelian subgroup for any group <m>G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-center-is-group-iff-abelian">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> be a group. Prove <m>G</m> is abelian if any only if <m>G=Z(G)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-centers-and-subgroups">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>H\leq G</m> be a subgroup. Prove <m>Z(H)\leq Z(G)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-gensubgp">
      <title>Generated Subgroups</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-gensubgp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given a group <m>G</m> and a subset <m>X</m> of <m>G</m>, the <em>subgroup of <m>G</m> generated by <m>X</m></em> is <me>\langle X \rangle := \bigcap_{H \leq G, H \supseteq X} H.</me> If <m>X=\{x\}</m> is a set with one element then we write <m>\langle X \rangle=\langle x \rangle</m> and we refer to this as the <em>cyclic subgroup generated by</em> <m>x</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <example xml:id="ex-commutator-subgroup">
        <p>
          Let <m>G</m> be a group, <m>S=\{aba\inv b\inv|a,b\in G\}</m>, and <m>G'=\igen S</m>. This is known as the <term>commutator subgroup</term> of <m>G</m>.
        </p>
      </example>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-gensubgp">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For a subset <m>X</m> of <m>G</m>, the elements of <m>\langle X \rangle</m> can be described as: 
            <me>
              \langle X \rangle = \left\{x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} \mid m \geq 0, j_1, \dots, j_m \in \mathbb{Z}\text{ and }x_1, \dots, x_m \in X \right\}.
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>S= \left\{x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} \mid m \geq 0, j_1, \dots, j_m \in \mathbb{Z}\text{ and }x_1, \dots, x_m \in X \right\}</m>. Since <m>\langle X \rangle</m> is a subgroup that contains <m>X</m>, it is closed under products and inverses, and thus must contain all elements of <m>S</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            For the opposite containment, we just need to show the set <m>S</m> really is a subgroup. We use the one step test:
          </p>
  
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>S \ne \emptyset</m> since we allow <m>m = 0</m> and declare the empty product to be <m>e_G</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m}</m> and <m>y_1^{i_1} \cdots y_n^{i_m}</m> are in <m>S</m> then 
                  <me>
                    x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m}(y_1^{i_1} \cdots y_n^{i_m})^{-1}=x_1^{j_1} \cdots x_m^{j_m} y_n^{-i_m} \cdots y_1^{-i_1}
                  </me> 
                  is also in <m>S</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
    
          <p>
            Therefore <m>S\leq G</m> and <m>X\subseteq S</m> (by taking <m>m=1</m> and <m>j_1=1</m>) and by the minimality of <m>\langle X \rangle</m> we obtain <m>\langle X \rangle\subseteq S</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <corollary>
        <statement>
        <p>
           <m>\langle x\rangle=\{x^j \mid j\in \mathbb{Z}\}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      </corollary>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-generating-an">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>A_n</m> is the subgroup of <m>S_n</m> generated by all produts of <m>2</m>-cyclies (disjoint or not). In symbols, 
          <me>
            A_n=\langle (i \ j )(k \ l) \mid i,j,k,l \in \{1, \ldots, n\}\rangle.
          </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

